<TITLE> Malaysia postpones trial in Mongolian murder case </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 SHAH ALAM, Malaysia, June 4 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Malaysia postponed on Monday the trial of a prominent political analyst accused of involvement in the murder of a Mongolian model in a case that has unfurled a frenzy of speculation about possible government links. The high court trial of Abdul Razak Abdullah Baginda, a close aide of Malaysia's deputy prime minister, was set to have run for a month, but a judge adjourned it until June 18 after government prosecutors replaced their legal team at the eleventh hour. The postponement drew a sharp protest from the Mongolian government, the family of the murdered model, 28-year-old Altantuya Shaariibuu, and lawyers for the defence. "Her father has lost confidence over how things are being handled," said Syed Abdul Rahman Alhabshi, Mongolia's honorary counsul-general in Malaysia, told reporters. Shaariibuu was shot in the head twice and her body blown up with plastic explosives in a jungle outside the Malaysian capital last October. Razak was charged with abetting the murder while two policemen were charged with murder. All three have pleaded not guilty, but all face mandatory death by hanging if convicted. The case was not a straightforward murder trial, prosecutor Tun Majid Tun Hamzah said while asking for additional time. Separately, Shaariibuu's family filed on Monday a $29 million civil suit against the three accused, and the Malaysian government for causing them mental shock and trauma
